---
import PageShell from '../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-system', text: 'Italian Healthcare System', level: 2 },
  { id: 'ssn-enrollment', text: 'SSN Enrollment', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-requirements', text: 'Visa Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-plans', text: 'Recommended Plans', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Expected Costs', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global in Italy', href: '/countries/italy/insurance/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Allianz Care in Italy', href: '/countries/italy/insurance/allianz-care' },
  { title: 'BUPA Global in Italy', href: '/countries/italy/insurance/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'IMG Global in Italy', href: '/countries/italy/insurance/img-global' },
  { title: 'Insurance for Digital Nomads', href: '/insurance-for/digital-nomads' },
  { title: 'Insurance for Retirees', href: '/insurance-for/retirees' },
];

const faqs = [
  {
    question: "Do I need private health insurance for an Italian visa?",
    answer: "Yes, most non-EU visa applicants need private health insurance for their initial application. This includes Elective Residence visas, student visas, and digital nomad visas. Work visas with Italian employer contracts may qualify directly for SSN enrollment."
  },
  {
    question: "Can expats use Italy's public healthcare system?",
    answer: "Yes, legal residents can enroll in the SSN (Servizio Sanitario Nazionale). EU citizens use their EHIC/GHIC initially. Non-EU visa holders typically need private insurance first, then can enroll in SSN once they have residency (permesso di soggiorno)."
  },
  {
    question: "How much does health insurance cost in Italy?",
    answer: "SSN enrollment is free or low-cost for employed residents. Private international insurance ranges from €100-300/month depending on age and coverage. Local Italian private insurance can be cheaper at €50-150/month but may have more restrictions."
  },
  {
    question: "What's the healthcare quality like in Italy?",
    answer: "Italy has excellent healthcare, ranked among Europe's best. Northern regions (Lombardy, Emilia-Romagna, Veneto) are particularly well-regarded. Public hospitals provide high-quality care, though wait times can be longer than private facilities."
  }
];

const planColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'type', header: 'Type' },
  { key: 'bestFor', header: 'Best For' },
  { key: 'startingPrice', header: 'From' },
];

const planRows = [
  { provider: 'SSN (Public)', type: 'Public System', bestFor: 'Long-term residents', startingPrice: 'Free/€400yr' },
  { provider: 'IMG Global', type: 'International', bestFor: 'Budget visa compliance', startingPrice: '€100/mo' },
  { provider: 'SafetyWing', type: 'Travel Medical', bestFor: 'Digital nomads, short stays', startingPrice: '€45/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', type: 'International', bestFor: 'High deductible savings', startingPrice: '€150/mo' },
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', type: 'International', bestFor: 'Comprehensive, English support', startingPrice: '€200/mo' },
  { provider: 'BUPA Global', type: 'International', bestFor: 'Mental health, pre-existing', startingPrice: '€250/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Expats in Italy"
  description="Complete guide to health insurance for expats in Italy. Understand SSN enrollment, visa requirements, and recommended international and local insurance options."
  headline="Health Insurance for Expats in Italy"
  subheadline="Navigate Italy's healthcare system as an expat—from visa insurance requirements to SSN enrollment and private coverage options."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/countries/italy-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Italy Plans →"
  ctaButtonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>
  <p>
    Italy offers excellent healthcare through its national system, the Servizio Sanitario Nazionale (SSN). For expats, the path to coverage depends on your visa type, employment status, and how long you plan to stay.
  </p>
  <p>
    Most expats follow this pattern: private international insurance for the visa application and initial period, then transition to SSN once residency is established. Some keep international coverage alongside SSN for shorter wait times, English-speaking providers, or coverage when traveling.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Moving to Italy?"
    description="Get the health insurance you need for your visa application and peace of mind."
    buttonText="See Italy Plans →"
    buttonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="healthcare-system">Italian Healthcare System</h2>
  <p>
    Italy's healthcare system consistently ranks among the world's best—the WHO ranked it 2nd globally. The system is regionally managed, which means quality and wait times vary by location.
  </p>

  <h3>How Italian Healthcare Works</h3>
  <p>
    The SSN provides universal coverage to residents. Care is largely free at the point of service, with small co-pays (ticket) for some services.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Tessera Sanitaria:</strong> Your health card for accessing SSN services</li>
    <li><strong>Medico di base:</strong> Your assigned general practitioner (GP)</li>
    <li><strong>ASL (Azienda Sanitaria Locale):</strong> Local health authority where you register</li>
    <li><strong>Ticket:</strong> Small co-pays for prescriptions and some services</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Regional Differences</h3>
  <p>
    Healthcare quality varies significantly by region:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Northern Italy (Lombardy, Emilia-Romagna, Veneto):</strong> Generally considered the best healthcare regions</li>
    <li><strong>Central Italy (Tuscany, Lazio):</strong> Good quality, Rome has many international-friendly hospitals</li>
    <li><strong>Southern Italy:</strong> Good care available but longer wait times and fewer resources</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Public vs Private Care</h3>
  <p>
    Many Italians use a mix of public and private care. Common patterns:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>GP visits, emergencies, hospitalizations:</strong> Public (SSN)</li>
    <li><strong>Specialist visits, diagnostics:</strong> Often private to skip wait times</li>
    <li><strong>Routine care:</strong> Public with ticket co-pays</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="ssn-enrollment">SSN Enrollment</h2>
  <p>
    Enrolling in the Italian public health system requires legal residency and registration at your local ASL.
  </p>

  <h3>Who Can Enroll</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>EU/EEA citizens:</strong> Immediate enrollment with residency registration</li>
    <li><strong>Employed workers:</strong> Enrolled automatically through employer contributions</li>
    <li><strong>Self-employed:</strong> Can enroll by paying contributions (around €400/year)</li>
    <li><strong>Retired expats:</strong> Can enroll voluntarily (Elective Residence visa holders)</li>
    <li><strong>Students:</strong> Can enroll or use private insurance</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Enrollment Process</h3>
  <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-2">
    <li>Obtain your permesso di soggiorno (residence permit)</li>
    <li>Register residency at your local Comune (town hall)</li>
    <li>Go to your local ASL with documents (permit, codice fiscale, proof of address)</li>
    <li>Complete enrollment and receive your Tessera Sanitaria</li>
    <li>Choose a medico di base from the available list</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Processing Times</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      The permesso di soggiorno can take several months to process. During this time, you'll rely on your private insurance. Don't let coverage lapse—processing delays are common.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="visa-requirements">Visa Requirements</h2>
  <p>
    Health insurance requirements vary by visa type. Most non-EU applicants need to show proof of coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Elective Residence Visa (Retirement)</h3>
  <p>
    Popular with retirees and those with passive income. Requirements:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Proof of income (typically €31,000+/year minimum)</li>
    <li><strong>Comprehensive health insurance valid in Italy</strong></li>
    <li>Coverage for entire visa duration</li>
    <li>Plan must cover hospitalization and emergency care</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Digital Nomad Visa (New in 2024)</h3>
  <p>
    Italy's new remote worker visa launched in 2024. Requirements:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Proof of remote work for non-Italian employer</li>
    <li>Minimum income requirement (€28,000+/year)</li>
    <li><strong>Health insurance meeting Italian standards</strong></li>
    <li>Coverage must be valid for visa duration</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Student Visa</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Health insurance required for visa application</li>
    <li>Can enroll in SSN once in Italy (around €150/year for students)</li>
    <li>Many use travel insurance initially, then switch to SSN</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Work Visa</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Employer-sponsored visas may not require separate insurance proof</li>
    <li>SSN enrollment comes through employment contract</li>
    <li>Some employers provide supplementary private coverage</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="recommended-plans">Recommended Plans</h2>
  <p>
    The best insurance choice depends on your visa type, length of stay, and healthcare preferences.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={planColumns} rows={planRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>For Visa Applications</h3>
  <p>
    You need comprehensive coverage that meets Italian consulate requirements:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global Gold/Platinum:</strong> Widely accepted, English support, meets requirements</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good for those wanting high-deductible savings</li>
    <li><strong>IMG Global:</strong> Budget-friendly option that meets visa requirements</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>For Digital Nomads</h3>
  <p>
    If you're on the digital nomad visa and may move between countries:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>SafetyWing:</strong> Affordable, designed for nomads, but travel medical (not comprehensive)</li>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Comprehensive worldwide coverage, portable if you relocate</li>
    <li><strong>World Nomads:</strong> Travel insurance option for shorter stays</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>For Long-Term Residents</h3>
  <p>
    Once you have SSN access, international insurance becomes optional but useful for:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Skipping public system wait times for specialists</li>
    <li>Access to private hospitals and English-speaking doctors</li>
    <li>Coverage when traveling outside Italy</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Find Your Italy Coverage"
    description="Compare plans that meet Italian visa requirements and your healthcare needs."
    buttonText="Compare Plans"
    buttonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
  />

  <h2 id="costs">Expected Costs</h2>

  <h3>Public Healthcare (SSN)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Employed workers:</strong> Free (funded through payroll contributions)</li>
    <li><strong>Self-employed/Voluntary:</strong> ~€400/year</li>
    <li><strong>Students:</strong> ~€150/year</li>
    <li><strong>Ticket co-pays:</strong> €0-50 for most services</li>
    <li><strong>Prescriptions:</strong> €2-5 for most medications</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Private International Insurance</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Budget plans (IMG, SafetyWing):</strong> €45-120/month</li>
    <li><strong>Mid-range (Allianz, Cigna Silver):</strong> €150-220/month</li>
    <li><strong>Comprehensive (Cigna Gold, BUPA):</strong> €200-350/month</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Private Italian Insurance</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Basic plans:</strong> €50-100/month</li>
    <li><strong>Comprehensive plans:</strong> €100-200/month</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Local Italian insurers like UniSalute, Previmedical, or Generali offer plans but typically require Italian language skills and have more restrictions than international plans.
  </p>

  <h3>Out-of-Pocket Private Care</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>GP visit (private):</strong> €80-150</li>
    <li><strong>Specialist visit:</strong> €100-200</li>
    <li><strong>MRI scan:</strong> €200-400</li>
    <li><strong>Hospital stay (private room):</strong> €300-600/night</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <h3>Do I need private insurance if I have SSN?</h3>
  <p>
    Not required, but many expats keep it for faster access to specialists, private hospital options, English-speaking care, and travel coverage. It's a personal choice based on budget and preferences.
  </p>

  <h3>How long until I can enroll in SSN?</h3>
  <p>
    Timing varies. EU citizens can enroll quickly after residency registration. Non-EU citizens need their permesso di soggiorno, which can take 3-6 months or longer. Keep private insurance until you have your Tessera Sanitaria.
  </p>

  <h3>Is SafetyWing enough for Italy?</h3>
  <p>
    SafetyWing is travel medical insurance, not comprehensive health insurance. It may not meet visa requirements for long-stay visas. It works well for digital nomads on shorter stays or as supplementary coverage, but verify with your consulate.
  </p>

  <h3>Can I see an English-speaking doctor?</h3>
  <p>
    In major cities (Rome, Milan, Florence), you'll find English-speaking doctors in private clinics and international hospitals. In smaller towns and through the public system, Italian language skills are more important.
  </p>

  <h3>What about pre-existing conditions?</h3>
  <p>
    SSN covers pre-existing conditions once you're enrolled. International insurers vary—BUPA Global is known for better pre-existing condition coverage. Review policy terms carefully before purchasing.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Move to Italy?"
    description="Get the health insurance you need for your visa and peace of mind."
    buttonText="Compare Plans Now"
    buttonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes only. Italian visa requirements, SSN enrollment rules, and healthcare policies change. Verify all information with Italian authorities and consult with immigration professionals before making decisions.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
